<HL>
   Medical Supply Firms Expected to Post
   Growth of 14% in First-Quarter Profit
   ----
   By R. Gustav Niebuhr
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7C
</SO>
<CO>
   ABT HUM NME BCR BAX
</CO>
<IN>
MEDICAL SUPPLIES (MDS)
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
</IN>
<LP>
   The nation's health-care companies are expected to finish
the first quarter in robust shape.
   Medical-supply firms are expected to report earnings
growth of about 14% on average, analysts said, even though
sales growth has remained at about 10% over the past two
quarters -- a reflection of the medical industry's efforts to
hold down expenditures.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the industry may face the threat of an economic
slowdown in 1990, an occurence that analysts said could
prompt insurers to further intensify pressure on hospitals to
cut costs. But even then, analysts add, the effect might be
minimal on suppliers, which have managed to hold down their
prices in recent quarters.
   Among the medical-supply concerns, Abbott Laboratories is
expected to report 15% growth in first-quarter earnings.
Sales for the Abbott Park, Ill., medical supplier rose 11% in
the fourth quarter to $1.46 billion, topping an 8.3% rise the
previous quarter.
   Baxter International Inc. is expected to report a 14%
increase in net income, with per-share earnings of 39 cents,
up from 34 cents a year ago. The Deerfield, Ill., company is
"on the verge of a significant restructuring move" that may
include corporate staff cuts and the sale of assets, said
David J. Lothson, an analyst with PaineWebber Inc.
   A few companies aren't likely to share in the overall
bright outlook. C.R. Bard Inc. is expected to report a 58%
drop in earnings, to about 16 cents a share from 38 cents a
year earlier. Since last summer, the Murray Hill, N.J.,
company has had to pull three angioplasty catheters from the
market after the Food and Drug Administration raised
questions about their design. The company is awaiting
approval to reintroduce the products.
   Hospital-management companies, benefiting from
restructuring and stabilized admission rates, continue to
report strong earnings.
   Despite some softness in the market for adolescent
psychiatric services, Los Angeles-based National Medical
Enterprises Inc. yesterday reported net income of $62.7
million, or 77 cents a share for its third quarter, ended
Feb. 28, up from $49.4 million, or 67 cents a share, a year
earlier.
   Humana Inc. reported earnings of $75.8 million, or 75
cents a share, for its second quarter, ended Feb. 28,
compared with $62.4 million, or 63 cents a share, in the
year-ago period. Analysts praised the Louisville, Ky., care
provider for securing a supply of patients for its hospitals
by boosting enrollment in its health maintenance
organizations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0184
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900402-0184.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Grand Met Expects
   15% Profit Rise
   In Fiscal 1990
   ----
   By Richard Gibson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   U.GME
</CO>
<IN>
RESTAURANTS, SUPERMARKETS AND DRUGSTORES (RFD)
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   MIAMI -- Grand Metropolitan PLC expects a 15% increase in
earnings per share in fiscal 1990 and believes that its U.S.
businesses will generate half its profits, Chairman Allen
Sheppard predicted.
   The forecast assumes a 5% inflation rate and 10% real
earnings growth, Mr. Sheppard said. In the year ended last
Sept. 30, the London-based food, retailing and drinks concern
posted per-share earnings of 55.6 pence, an 18.5% gain from
fiscal 1988.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Sheppard made his prediction while addressing
analysts, primarily from Britain, who this week toured some
of Grand Met's U.S. properties, including Heublein
distillers, Pearle health services, Pillsbury food and the
Burger King fast-food chain.
   Contending that "we don't have any bad businesses," Mr.
Sheppard said Grand Met will concentrate near-term on
expanding Burger King and Pearle as "international
brandings," while developing "critical mass" for its food
businesses in Central Europe.
   "We're looking for a stable of international brands --
that's our strategy," Mr. Sheppard said, adding that Grand
Met also is searching for "another Pearle that everybody else
has missed in service retailing."
   Mr. Sheppard and Group Finance Director David Nash also
said they hope to have Grand Met American Depositary Receipts
listed on the New York Stock Exchange by September. ADRs are
receipts for shares of a foreign-based corporation, which
trade much like stock in the U.S.
   "If we list I'd like to be able to issue some stock," Mr.
Nash said, indicating a total offering of perhaps $100
million. He and other Grand Met executives told analysts they
would expect considerable demand for such an offering in the
U.S.
   Grand Met has received the first round of bids for its
U.S.-based Alpo Petfoods Inc. unit and is "in the middle of
conversations with a number of serious purchasers," the
company said.
   Grand Met recently put Alpo up for sale because its goal
of building it into a billion-dollar business seemed
unobtainable, said Ian Martin, chief executive of Grand Met's
food sector.
   Mr. Martin termed Alpo's recent entry into the cat-food
business "very successful." Although its market share is only
around 1%, he said would-be buyers have been "surprised at
the success" of the new business.
   Reviewing Grand Met's extensive retailing (licensed
restaurants) group in Europe, Mr. Sheppard acknowledged that
Grand Met had "misread" the eating-out market in the United
Kingdom but is "back on track now."
   As for overseas expansion of Pillsbury brands, Mr. Martin
said he foresees "significant" opportunities for Green Giant
vegetables and Haagen-Dazs premium ice cream. He said the
company is seriously considering building a Haagen-Dazs plant
somewhere in Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
