<HL>
   American Continental
   Suit Citing Regulators
   Is Dismissed by Court
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   AMC
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   PHOENIX, Ariz. -- A federal judge dismissed the lawsuit of
American Continental Corp. against federal regulators it had
accused of damaging its Lincoln Savings &amp; Loan Association
subsidiary by leaking confidential information to the press.
   Federal Judge Richard M. Bilby acted on a motion by
American Continental to dismiss the case without prejudice,
meaning that it may be refiled or reopened. But Judge Bilby
added that unless American Continental takes action by July
1, the case would be dismissed with prejudice.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   American Continental filed for reorganization under
Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code last April 13. The
government seized Lincoln Savings, of Irvine, Calif., the
next day. More than 23,000 investors claim they weren't
warned of the risks in buying uninsured junk bonds of Lincoln
Savings. They lost $200 million when the thrift failed.
   Judge Bilby precipitated the company's March 7 dismissal
motion when he barred American Continental from continuing to
pay attorneys to pursue the case. He said he feared that
attorneys' fees would use up the equity in American
Continental.
   James Feder, an attorney for American Continental, said it
wasn't clear whether the firm will attempt to refile or
reopen the suit. "We don't have the time and resources to
pursue this suit with the other litigation we have going," he
said.
   Government regulators have estimated that the Lincoln
failure may cost taxpayers $2 billion.
   American Continental had argued that top thrift regulators
regularly leaked information to the press that hurt the
survival possibilities of Lincoln Savings. Named as
defendants were M. Danny Wall, former director of the Office
of Thrift Supervision; Darrel W. Dochow, acting principal
supervisory agent for Lincoln, and William K. Black, general
counsel of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board in San Francisco.
   The defendants couldn't be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0164
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900402-0164.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Great Pacific Capital
   Increases to 11.13%
   Its Stake in Ipco Corp.
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   IHS
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. -- Great Pacific Capital Ltd., a New
York investment concern owned by a Canadian financier, Jim
Pattison, said it raised to 11.13% its stake in Ipco Corp.'s
common shares outstanding from 9.37% last November.
   In a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, Great
Pacific said it holds 563,600 Ipco shares, including 77,800
acquired between Jan. 30 and Tuesday, for $7.125 to $8.125
each. In New York Stock Exchange composite trading Friday,
Ipco shares closed at $7.75, down 25 cents.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ipco operates a chain of about 250 Sterling Optical and
Ipco Optical stores in 20 U.S. states and Canada, which
generated earnings last year of about $453,000 on sales of
$123.9 million.
   Ipco officials weren't available to comment on the filing,
and a Great Pacific executive wouldn't elaborate. Great
Pacific said previously that it may buy additional Ipco
shares or "make a proposal with respect to a business
combination," among other things, depending on market
conditions and other factors.
   Mr. Pattison, based in Vancouver, British Columbia, has
various closely held companies that generate aggregate annual
sales of more than two billion Canadian dollars (US$1.71
billion). He formed Great Pacific in 1987 to search for U.S.
acquisitions.
   In a recent interview, Mr. Pattison said that he wants to
acquire U.S. assets to help diversify his holdings, and that
he is mainly interested in retail or consumer product
companies. "We're comfortable serving the public," he said.
Mr. Pattison's holdings include car dealerships, grocery
stores, and advertising and packaging companies.
</TEXT>
