<HL>
   Technology:
   U.K. Study Finds
   Protein Linked
   With Alzheimer's
   ----
   By Joann S. Lublin
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7A
</SO>
<IN>
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- A British study found a defective blood protein
that may help develop the first diagnostic test for
Alzheimer's disease, an incurable, mind-destroying ailment
common among the elderly.
   The research also signifies the first time scientists have
uncovered a possible explanation for why aluminum builds up
in brain cells of Alzheimer's patients. Aluminum long has
been suspected to play a role in the debilitating
neurological disorder, which afflicts about 2.5 million
Americans and kills 100,000 a year. In Britain, about 750,000
people suffer from the disease.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   At present, doctors lack a clear-cut way to diagnose the
illness in a patient, except by eliminating other possible
causes for mental deterioration.
   The small-scale study suggests aluminum may accumulate in
brains of Alzheimer's patients because they have defective
transferrin, a blood protein to which aluminium normally
binds in the blood stream.
   "People without this defect would be protected from the
neurotoxic effects of aluminum," concludes the report in this
week's issue of Lancet, a U.K. medical journal. "The presence
of the defect could be used as a diagnostic test for
Alzheimer's disease," adds the report, written by nine
British and French researchers.
   Paul Altmann, a nephrologist at London Hospital and one of
the study's authors, said the research "is quite an important
step forward" in understanding Alzheimer's disease. If
scientists can use the research to craft a simple diagnostic
blood test, he added, "it opens the door to developing the
therapeutic maneuvers in the future. But these are things
that will take some time to develop."
   Other Alzheimer's experts were even more cautious. The
finding "sounds promising. But a great deal more work has to
be done to test this hypothesis," said Nora Graham, chairman
of Britain's Alzheimer's Disease Society and a London
neuro-geriatrician.
   John Candy, a neuro-scientist at England's Newcastle
General Hospital, criticized the research's methodology as
flawed. "I remain skeptical," he said.
   In the Lancet study, the scientists analyzed blood samples
from 62 individuals divided into five groups: a control
group, plus patients undergoing kidney dialysis and patients
with Alzheimer's, stroke-related dementia or a form of mental
retardation called Down's syndrome. The investigators used
gallium, a metal similar to aluminum, to measure whether
aluminum's binding to transferrin was impaired.
   Significant impairment showed up in both Alzheimer's and
Down's syndrome patients. For these patients, "the amount of
binding to transferrin is less than half the normal amount,"
said Dr. Altmann. Transferrin "doesn't detoxify the metal"
and so more aluminum apparently slips into the patients'
brain cells. "This whole story strengthens the evidence for
aluminum playing a role" in Alzheimer's disease, he added.
   Previous research has found aluminum deposits in brain
cells damaged by Alzheimer's disease and Down's syndrome.
Down's syndrome patients also tend to develop Alzheimer's
later in life. In January 1989, a British government study
concluded that adults who consume water with high
concentrations of aluminum run a 50% greater risk of
developing Alzheimer's disease than people whose water
contains virtually no aluminum.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0144
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900402-0144.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   West German Plan
   On Mark Exchange
   Stirs Ire in East
   ----
   By Terence Roth and Mark M. Nelson
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   The Bundesbank's proposal for a 2-to-1 conversion rate for
East German marks into West German marks triggered an uproar
in East Germany.
   The recommendation by Bundesbank President Karl-Otto Poehl
at a meeting of European Community finance ministers and
central bank governors in Galway, Ireland, marked a retreat
from pledges made by West German leaders during recent East
German elections. Mr. Poehl said a 1-to-1 conversion rate
should be limited to a maximum 2,000 marks per East German
citizen. The rest of East German savings, debt and wages
would be converted at the rate of two East marks for one West
German mark. A West German mark has a value of 59 U.S. cents
at current exchange rates.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Furious East Berlin officials warned that anything less
than a broadly implemented 1-for-1 rate would impoverish most
East German wage earners and even hinder the unification of
the two Germanys. Leaders of the major East German parties
joined together over the weekend to reject the plan, and East
German Premier Hans Modrow said in a newspaper interview the
proposal has already stirred widespread unrest in the East
German population. He insisted that West German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl and other Bonn officials had promised East German
savers a 1-for-1 rate in the run-up to East Germany's March
18 election, which resulted in a landside victory for
Bonn-supported conservatives.
   "The election result was the result of these promises, and
nothing else," Mr. Modrow declared. The head of the caretaker
government insisted that East Germans had interpreted the
promises as having a broad application, including wages.
   Mr. Modrow warned that Bonn would be held responsible for
any strikes or demonstrations that might result from the
apparent policy shift. Officials for the East German
Christian Democrats reported that their East Berlin
headquarters was flooded with calls from angry citizens.
   Rainer Eppelmann, head of the Democratic Awakening party,
one of the three East German parties making up the CDU-led
conservative alliance, predicted a fresh wave of emigration
to West Germany.
   The proposal unsettled Mr. Kohl's allies back in Bonn.
Otto Lambsdorff, head of the Free Democratic Party, the
junior partner in the Bonn government coalition, told a
newspaper the proposal could be seen as "a breach of faith."
   East Germans can now buy West German marks at a subsidized
rate of one for each three East marks. Monetary officials
calculate the East mark's true purchasing power suggests a
rate of 4.4 to one. Even a 2-to-1 rate would be a vast
improvement for East German workers, they say.
   While the West German government hasn't accepted the
2-for-1 proposal, Finance Minister Theo Waigel said it was
"economically and financially well founded" and that it
couldn't be ignored, while Economics Minister Helmut
Haussmann called the recommendation an "important decision"
that wouldn't inflict economic harm on East Germans.
   While unpopular among the populace, a 2-for-1 rate would
be a boon to highly indebted East German state companies,
which wouldn't have to use as much hard currency to pay off
debts, and would make East German companies more competitive
with Western ones. Such a rate would also be less
inflationary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0143
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900402-0143.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   At New York News
   Threat of Strike
   Is Looming Larger
   ----
   By Patrick M. Reilly
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7G
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR TRB
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The threat of a strike at the troubled New
York Daily News looms larger than ever following the
expiration on Friday of a contract covering the 10 unions at
the country's largest metropolitan daily newspaper.
   Both Daily News management and union leaders remain at the
bargaining table. However, after months of bitter verbal
attacks by both sides, there's no sign of a truce. Observers
of the negotiations say the Daily News, which is owned by
Chicago-based Tribune Co., could face a walkout by union
members within a month.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The industry's most acrimonious newspaper labor battle in
years comes at a bad time for the Daily News, which has
posted losses for most of the last decade. It faces increased
competition from another tabloid, Times Mirror Co.'s New York
Newsday, at a time when the New York advertising market is
the softest in years.
   Almost every scenario the Daily News faces is a dire one,
at least for the near future. Management has demanded major
cost and work concessions from the unions and says it is
prepared to publish and distribute the paper in the event of
a strike. Even so, the Daily News stands to lose significant
advertising and circulation.
   Union leaders say they hope to avoid a strike, yet several
of the unions have voted strike authorizations. Many workers
face the loss of their jobs permanently if they do walk off
their jobs. If there is a strike, the unions threaten to lead
a boycott of the paper by readers and advertisers.
   The 1980s nearly ruined the Daily News and strained
Tribune Co.'s commitment to publishing in New York. The Daily
News had revenue of $420 million in 1989, yet the paper was
only marginally profitable. Over the past decade, the paper
has lost $115 million on $4 billion in revenue. Average daily
paid circulation has fallen by 400,000 copies since 1979; as
of Sept. 30, 1989, the paper's circulation was 1.2 million,
down 7% from 1988.
   The union is charging mismanagement, and claims the
Tribune intends to win concessions, then sell off the
newspaper. James Hoge, publisher of the Daily News, is "a
sociable guy, but as a publisher he's a 4 on a scale of 1 to
10," said George McDonald, president of the Allied Printing
Trades Council. "The News has bum management."
   Daily News executives blame the heavy financial burden of
a bloated union work force. About 50% of the paper's revenue
goes to cover employee compensation, compared with 25% to 30%
at most other major metropolitan papers.
   As for selling the paper, media analysts doubt it will
take place. "New York is the biggest media market in the U.S.
The Tribune won't give that up," said Peter Appert, analyst
at C.J. Lawrence. "If they can get even a mediocre profit
from that huge base of revenues, it's worth pursuing."
   The troubling situation is a familiar one for Tribune Co.
In 1985, at the company's flagship Chicago Tribune, the
pressmen and printers unions were broken in a prolonged and
violent strike. The Tribune management won control of hiring
and eliminated costly labor abuses. The Daily News is looking
for the same and Mr. Hoge claims that with concessions in
hand, the Tribune will invest $500 million in new presses
able to print color pages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0142
</DOCNO>
