<HL>
   The Outlook:
   Impact of Profit Drop
   May Have Lessened
   ----
   By Alfred L. Malabre Jr.
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Perhaps the most remarkable feature of the economy's
ability to keep expanding despite so many well-publicized
problems involves profits, which are supposed to be
capitalism's lifeblood. It's true, as Edward Yardeni,
economics director for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.,
observes, that "corporate profits have been in a recession
since the second quarter of last year." Yet, as the second
quarter of 1990 begins, the general level of business
activity appears still to be rising, and most forecasters
share Mr. Yardeni's view that "the economy will grow all
year." How, with profits sagging, is such an economic
performance possible?
   The explanation, according to Lacy H. Hunt, chief
economist of the investment firm of Carroll McEntree &amp;
McGinley Inc., is that profits occupy a sharply diminished
role in today's economy. He reckons, accordingly, that to
drag the economy into a new recession profits would have to
decline far longer and more steeply than they have done so
far. He doubts this will happen and endorses the consensus
forecast that the economy will continue to expand, at the
least, through 1990.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   The shrinking role of profits is evident, as Mr. Hunt
says, in comparisons of profits and the gross national
product, the broadest measure of overall economic activity.
In the 1960s, amid the longest economic expansion in the
history of the U.S. business cycle, corporate profits,
adjusted for inventory gains or losses and for depreciation,
reached 11.7% of GNP. This percentage fell to a low of 6.9%
near the trough of the subsequent 1969-70 recession. Since
then, as the chart below shows, the pattern has been for the
percentages to be lower at both expansionary high points and
recessionary low points.
                                                                                                       

   The latest reading, for last year's fourth quarter, is
5.3%. This is appreciably below the high for this expansion
of 7.3%, set in the second quarter of 1984, but it remains
well above the low for the 1981-82 recession of 4.5%. It also
is substantially higher than where Mr. Hunt, given the
pattern of progressively falling levels of both the high and
low readings, places the new "recessionary range." For him to
become concerned about profits dragging the economy into a
recession in coming months, he says, they would have to fall
to about 3% of GNP.
   Mr. Hunt shares the view of most forecasters that such a
decline will not occur. The consensus is that economic growth
will slowly accelerate as the year goes along, and in the
process profits will increase. For instance, 51 forecasters
polled by Blue Chip Economic Indicators of Sedona, Ariz.,
estimate on average that the economy will grow 2.3% annually
in the year's last half and profits will rise as well.
   In the last three months of 1989, pretax profits continued
a decline that began early last year. But the rate of decline
slowed markedly to 0.5% from 7.1% in the previous quarter.
And, on an after-tax basis, profits edged up in the quarter,
reversing a yearlong slide.
   Profits, it should be noted, tend to lead the economy's
ups and downs. The government, in fact, continues to classify
them as a leading economic indicator, normally rising or
falling several months before such broader gauges as
employment and industrial production follow suit. Mr. Hunt
agrees that profits still tend to lead the economy, but he
adds that nowadays "the economy clearly can manage to keep
expanding through the sort of profit decline that once would
have signaled a recession."
   One reason, he says, is that service businesses, which
tend to operate on slimmer profit margins, now play a larger
economic role. More importantly, the huge increase in
corporate indebtedness in recent years has served to reduce
profits. Corporations' net interest costs -- interest expense
less interest income -- reached a record 52% of profits in
last year's fourth quarter, up from less than 2% a
quarter-century ago.
                                                                                                       

   The interest that corporations pay on their bonds and
other borrowings, of course, may be deducted from their
profits, reducing taxes. The upshot is that many firms that
have undergone leveraged restructuring now show weak profits
or lose money, and yet remain in operation, providing jobs
that help sustain overall economic activity.
                                                                                                       

   The economy, to be sure, cannot continue indefinitely to
expand if profits keep dropping. Many analysts, in fact,
attribute much of the economy's recent sluggishness to the
profit decline of the past year and its impact on corporate
hiring and spending. And some forecasters remain convinced
the profit decline signals a recession is near.
   Perhaps so. But with a reduced role for profits, that
possibility may prove less likely than in the past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0088
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900402-0088.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Medicare Pays Billions for Health Claims
   Covered by Private Plans, Report Finds
   ----
   By Walt Bogdanich
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<IN>
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<GV>
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Federal health officials need to plug holes
more aggressively in the Medicare program or risk losing
several billion dollars through unnecessary payments on
medical claims, a new report concludes.
   The Medicare program for the elderly has been losing as
much as $1 billion a year because it paid claims for which
private health plans were liable, according to the report
issued by Richard P. Kusserow, inspector general for the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   HHS's Health Care Financing Administration had proposed
new legislation that would have provided data it needed to
identify and stop the unnecessary payments, but the Office of
Management and Budget objected, and HHS consequently backed
off. That decision, said Mr. Kusserow, could cost the
Medicare program $2.7 billion in unnecessary payments over
the next five years. The dollar figure "is too large to
ignore," he said. While HCFA has taken some administrative
steps to identify the overpayments, he added, "none has
proven completely effective."
   HHS has known of these unnecessary payments for years, but
until recently did little to stop them, investigators found.
Nine insurance companies, including some of the nation's
largest, are now being investigated by federal authorities
for failing to pay claims.
   Mr. Kusserow, in a separate report, asked the HCFA to
pressure private health plans into reimbursing Medicare for
billions of dollars that should have been paid previously.
Under the inspector general's plan, insurers would have one
year to voluntarily make restitution, or be subject to treble
damages, plus costs, for each claim uncovered by the
government.
   The federal financing agency called Mr. Kusserow's
suggestion appealing, but thus far has failed to back it
fully. "We believe that the magnitude of the program losses .
. . compels us to take creative approaches, such as the
voluntary disclosure proposal," Mr. Kusserow said.
   Gail R. Wilensky, recently appointed director of HCFA,
said she wants to study the issues before deciding what to
do.
   In 1982, Congress tried to contain rising Medicare costs
by making Medicare a "secondary insurer" for the so-called
working aged. That made the employer-sponsored health plan
the "primary insurer" for any claimant whose employer
provided medical benefits.
   Federal health officials, however, made little effort to
identify those individuals who should have had their claims
paid by private health plans. One reason was because the
government turned over administration of the program to some
of the very insurance companies that stood to benefit from
erroneous payments. Some insurance companies looked the other
way when they discovered Medicare overpayments that benefited
their own companies, according to government investigators.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0087
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900402-0087.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Simpler Tax Rules Sought
   For Large Partnerships
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Treasury recommended drastically
simplifying the system for calculating the income tax of
widely held partnerships.
   In a report to the tax-writing Senate Finance and House
Ways and Means committees, the Treasury and the Internal
Revenue Service concluded that the requirements for reporting
income of large partnerships "are overly complex and
inefficient."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A simplified reporting system would ease the burden and
cost of compliance on partnerships and make it easier for the
IRS to administer that area of tax law, the two agencies
said.
   In general, the agencies are recommending radically
reducing the number of items that must be reported separately
to partners. Instead "all income and expense, including
capital gains and losses, would be netted at the partnership
level," the report said.
   "The goal of these proposed changes is not to increase or
decrease the overall tax due partnerships," the report said.
But it added, "We recognize that the total income tax
attributable to a partnership subject to the simplified
reporting system would almost certainly vary to some degree
from the total income tax under the current rules."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0086
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900402-0086.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   McCaw Cellular Files
   With SEC for Sale
   Of 2.4 Million Shares
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5A
</SO>
<CO>
   MCAWA AFP
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. -- McCaw Cellular Communications Inc.
filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission for the
sale of 2.4 million Class A shares. The shares are held by a
trust controlled by William Taylor, chairman of Affiliated
Publications Inc., and two of Affiliated's directors.
   The proposed offering is contingent on an offering by the
trust of 2.8 million Affiliated Publications Class A common
shares. The trust owns 12.8% of McCaw's Cellular's Class A
common, or 7.8% of the company's total common stock
outstanding.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the filing, McCaw said investment in the shares
involves a high degree of risk because the company expects
its net losses to increase significantly for the foreseeable
future and "may exceed $1 billion in some years." However, a
spokesman said a substantial part of the loss would be in
non-cash categories related to depreciation and amortization.
   McCaw officials weren't available for comment. A spokesman
said he didn't know for many years the company expected to
post a loss.
   In 1989, McCaw had a net loss of $288.5 million on revenue
of $504 million. The company has never posted a profit, as
its heavy marketing costs, debt and other expenses have been
a drag on earnings.
   However, in the fledgling cellular industry, cash flow and
subscriber growth are closely watched as the best indicators
of a company's progress. McCaw showed rapid growth in number
of subscribers and its cash flow increased in its most recent
quarter.
   In the filing, McCaw also said it has a large amount of
debt related to its recent acquisition of a controlling
interest in LIN Broadcasting Corp. McCaw said it has
long-term debt of about $3.1 billion, including about $1.4
billion under a credit agreement with a group of banks.
   McCaw said it doesn't expect its operations to generate
sufficient cash flow to service all of its debt for the next
several years. However, the company said it believes it will
be able to make the required interest payment primarily from
cash generated by operations and borrowings from its bank
credit facility.
   McCaw said it believes it and LIN have sufficient
internally generated funds to repay its debt at maturity.
Alternatively, the company said it believes it will be able
to make necessary repayments and repurchases through the
refinancing of the debt obligations, sales of equity or sales
of assets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
