<HL>
   International:
   Mexico Reopens Program
   To Swap Foreign Debt
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   MEXICO CITY -- Mexico reopened its debt-for-equity swap
program, which had been suspended since November 1987.
   Under the revamped program, $3.5 billion dollars in
Mexican foreign debt is to be swapped during the next 3 1/2
years for ownership interests in infrastructure projects and
state-owned companies undergoing public offerings. The
minimum discount the government said it would accept is 35
cents on the dollar of debt being swapped.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The new swap program is more limited in scope than the
original, in which banks traded debt outstanding for local
currency that was then used to buy into local companies. By
restricting the program to swaps of debt for infrastructure
or state-owned enterprises the government won't have to print
new money or issue more domestic debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0078
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900402-0078.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Rep. Bill Frenzel Says
   He Won't Seek Re-Election
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Minnesota Rep. Bill Frenzel, the ranking GOP
member of the House Budget Committee, said he won't run for
re-election.
   "Every member of Congress knows when the time has come not
to run again," said Mr. Frenzel, who is 61 years old, at a
St. Paul, Minn., news conference. "For me, it is now."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Frenzel, known for his quick wit and curmudgeonly
demeanor, has long fought for lower federal spending and
resisted raising taxes to reduce the budget deficit. A senior
member of the House Ways and Means Committee, Mr. Frenzel
also is a leading GOP voice on trade issues. He is currently
serving his 10th House term.
   The ranking GOP member on the budget committee is selected
by a vote of all House Republicans. Ohio Rep. Willis Gradison
is a leading contender to replace Mr. Frenzel.
</TEXT>
