<HL>
   U.S. Charges McHaffie
   With Falsifying Test Data
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5A
</SO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- McHaffie Inc., a Sylmar, Calif., defense
contractor, was charged by the U.S. Justice Department with
falsification of test data on bolts the company made for use
in various military jet aircraft engines.
   In a criminal information filed in federal court in Los
Angeles, the government alleged that McHaffie failed to test
the bolts and submitted fraudulent certifications to the
government over an eight-year period beginning in 1979. The
certifications indicated that the bolts had been tested and
met all manufacturing standards and other specifications, the
government charged.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The information named as defendants the company; its
56-year-old owner and president, Norman McHaffie, and two
employees, James Hicks, 45, and William Whitham, 37.
   Attorneys for Mr. McHaffie and Mr. Hicks said they hadn't
seen the information and couldn't comment. Neither Mr.
Whitham nor his attorney could be reached.
   The company faces a maximum fine of $1.5 million, the
government said. Mr. McHaffie faces a maximum sentence of 15
years in prison and a $750,000 fine. Messrs. Hicks and
Whitham, who cooperated with the government in its
investigation, each face a maximum sentence of 10 years in
prison and a $500,000 fine.
</TEXT>
