<HL>
   Ivaco Plans to Buy
   Remainder of Canron,
   A Toronto Steel Firm
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   IVA.A TCL.A
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   MONTREAL -- Ivaco Inc. and Canron Inc. said Ivaco agreed
to acquire the 21% of Canron it doesn't already own under a
proposed arrangement approved by the boards of both
companies.
   Ivaco and Canron said the arrangement is subject to
approval by regulatory authorities and Canron holders at a
meeting in May. Ivaco, a Montreal-based steel and
steel-products concern, said that under the arrangement it
will make an offer valued at about 42.6 million Canadian
dollars (US$36.3 million) for the publicly held shares of
Canron, a Toronto steel and pipe concern. Under the
arrangement, Ivaco said Canron holders would receive C$20.50
for each Class A or Class B share and C$35 for each Series B
preferred share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   On the Toronto Stock Exchange Canron Class A shares last
traded Friday before a trading halt at C$11.50, unchanged. In
Toronto, Ivaco Class A shares closed at C$10.25, down 25
Canadian cents.
   Paul Ivanier, president and chief executive officer of
Ivaco, said funding for the acquisition would come from the
combined resources of Ivaco and Canron.
   Both Ivaco and Canron have been struggling lately. Each
posted a loss for 1989 after extraordinary items and losses
from discontinued operations.
