<HL>
   Farley's West Point
   Unit Is in Default
   On Some Bank Debt
   ----
   By Robert Johnson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   WPM
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX)
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   William Farley's troubles with the acquisition of West
Point-Pepperell Inc. worsened when the unit he set up to buy
the company fell into default on about $733 million in bank
debt after negotiations to restructure the loan bogged down.
   According to a Wall Street person close to the
negotiations, Mr. Farley plans as soon as today to offer the
holders of roughly $905 million in West Point-Pepperell
subordinated debt a significant equity position in the
company in exchange for delaying interest payments for as
long as three years.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   If Mr. Farley is successful in the exchange offer to bond
holders, his bankers, led by Wells Fargo &amp; Co. and Bankers
Trust Co., are more likely to commit a restructuring of his
bank loan rather than forcing him into federal bankruptcy-law
proceedings.
   The bankers are known to be worried that the holders of
subordinated notes for which Mr. Farley might miss interest
payments in the next few months may force him into federal
bankruptcy-law proceedings.
   The bankers, concerned about the possible costs of paying
bankruptcy-law attorneys to oversee lengthy legal
proceedings, would take it as a good sign to see approval of
the forthcoming exchange offer on the subordinated notes.
   Farley officials couldn't be reached for comment over the
weekend, but they are known to be continuing negotiations
with bankers.
   Last month Mr. Farley successfully negotiated a $1.2
billion bridge-loan extension through the end of 1994, easing
some of the pressure on the West Point acquisition. But the
bank loan that was due Saturday is an additional debt that
was used to help make the tender offer in the $1.56 billion
West Point acquisition in March 1989.
   Of the several entities under the umbrella of Mr. Farley's
investment and industrial empire, the bank-loan default
affects only West Point-Pepperell Acquisition, the holding
company that was set up last year to acquire the West Point,
Ga.-based textile concern.
   Mr. Farley has completed his tender offer on 95% of West
Point-Pepperell. But he is about $83 million short of the
cash needed to complete the transaction. Unless he completes
that deal, he can't use West Point's cash to pay interest on
the debt it produced. Thus Mr. Farley's only chance to finish
the transaction and keep control of the company is to
restructure certain of his bank and subordinated note debt.
   Mr. Farley, based in Chicago, built a collection of
manufacturing companies, largely on junk bond financing. But
his investment banker, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., has
collapsed. Farley Inc., his closely held manufacturing
concern, had a pretax loss of about $40 million in 1989,
analysts estimated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0021
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900402-0021.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Andrus's Veto of Idaho Abortion Bill
   Fuels Controversy for November Election
   ----
   By David Shribman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5A
</SO>
<GV>
SUPREME COURT (SUP)
</GV>
<LP>
   Leaders of the drive to curb abortion are searching for
new opportunities to press their efforts after suffering a
substantial setback in Idaho.
   Meanwhile, abortion-rights activists are warning that
Democratic Gov. Cecil Andrus's veto of a restrictive abortion
bill in Idaho Friday night only highlights the fragility of
the right to abortion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Andrus, long considered an opponent of abortion,
startled many of his allies when he vetoed the Idaho bill,
which would have prevented about 95% of the state's
abortions. The governor, who in the past week had become the
focus of intense national lobbying, said the legislation was
"drawn so narrowly that it would punitively and without
compassion further harm an Idaho woman who may find herself
in the horrible, unthinkable position of confronting a
pregnancy that resulted from rape or incest."
   Mr. Andrus's veto of the legislation ends the issue in
Idaho this year. The state legislature adjourned for the year
Friday and, in any case, proponents of the bill lacked the
votes to override the veto.
   The legislation was drafted to prompt a U.S. Supreme Court
decision and was crafted with an eye toward appealing to
Associate Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, considered the high
court's swing vote on abortion issues.
   Abortion opponents, who had hoped that the Idaho bill
would spur the court to override the 1973 Roe vs. Wade
decision that established abortion rights, targeted Mr.
Andrus, who seeks re-election in November, for defeat.
   "This will go down as one of the greatest acts of
political treachery in American history," said Burke Balch,
state legislative director of the National Right to Life
Committee.
   Mr. Andrus's decision was made amid rallies and
counter-rallies at the state capitol in Boise and amid
threats, from the National Organization for Women and others,
that abortion-rights activists would boycott Idaho potatoes,
the state's largest commodity.
   The Idaho Republican Party already has signaled that it
will make abortion a major issue in the November election.
Democrats, meanwhile, indicated that they will resist efforts
from national organizations such as the National Right to
Life Committee to use what state Sen. Marti Calabretta, a
Democrat from northern Idaho, called "control and coercion."
   Kate Michelman, executive director of the National
Abortion Rights Action League, said Mr. Andrus had "refused
to rob women of their rights," but added, "We face the
reality that for every Cecil Andrus there's someone who
stands ready to limit our right to choose. It is in jeopardy
at every turn of the road."
   The anti-abortion movement still hopes to prevail in state
legislatures in Florida and Louisiana. "Idaho galvanizes the
pro-life movement," said Mr. Balch. "This isn't just a
defeat. It's a political betrayal that angers people around
the nation."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0020
</DOCNO>
