<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   COLUMBIA S&amp;L DISCLOSED it is insolvent, likely resulting
in a costly federal takeover. The big California thrift
posted a $379.1 million loss for the 1989 fourth quarter,
reflecting huge junk bond losses. Columbia was once the
nation's most profitable thrift due to its big stake in junk
bonds, many of them bought from Drexel and Michael Milken.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street's profits from underwriting stocks and bonds
teetered near six-year lows in the first quarter. And the
recent collapse of junk bonds promises even leaner times
ahead.
                                                                                                       

   Merrill Lynch continued to be the world's biggest
underwriter of stocks and bonds in the quarter, but its lead
shrank as financing volume eased.
   ---
   Tokyo stocks plunged 5.7% by Monday morning's close as the
dollar soared above 160 yen and institutions apparently began
a sell-off.
   ---
   Japanese trade negotiators will unveil a package of
proposed market-opening measures today, but the steps are
likely to disappoint the U.S.
   ---
   Southmark filed a new reorganization plan with the help of
unsecured creditors. The company hopes the plan may let it
emerge from Chapter 11 proceedings by July.
   ---
   A Farley company set up to buy West Point-Pepperell
defaulted on a $733 million bank loan after talks to
restructure the loan bogged down.
   ---
   Chrysler is asking its top 100 executives to own stock
equal to a certain percentage of their salaries. The unusual
program is aimed at having the officials bet more of their
pay on Chrysler's long-term financial health.
   ---
   McDonnell Douglas confirmed it won a $2 billion jet order
from Japan Air Lines that includes options for a stretched
version of the MD-11 jet.
   ---
   Factory orders rebounded 1.8% in February, helped by gains
in the auto sector. The increase followed a revised 5.5%
plunge the month before, the biggest in 15 years. Also, the
February rise in durable-goods orders was revised to 2.6%
from 3.3%.
                                                                                                       

   Fed policy makers voted in February to leave credit
unchanged. But for the first time in months, some officials
talked of raising rates.
   ---
   The Dallas investment firm Hicks Muse acquired seven
I.C.H. insurance units for $530 million, one of the first
major leveraged buy-outs since the UAL deal fell apart in
October.
   ---
   The American Heart Association is ending its controversial
seal-of-approval program for low-fat foods, sources said. The
FDA strongly objected to the two-month-old program.
   ---
   Thrift nominee Timothy Ryan may face a tough confirmation
fight on the Senate floor following the disclosure of his
drug use in the early 1970s. Ryan was narrowly approved
Friday by the Senate Banking Committee.
   ---
   Motorola was allowed by a U.S. court to continue selling
its key microchip, easing worries among computer makers about
a shortage. The decision came in a patent infringement case
involving Hitachi.
   ---
   Digital Equipment plans to unveil new engineering
workstations tomorrow, but they aren't as fast as the models
IBM introduced in February.
   ---
   The U.S. parent of Campeau's department store units filed
for Chapter 11, saying it was a "procedural step" in the
units' own reorganization.
   ---
   BTR filed suit to prevent Norton from canceling its April
26 annual meeting. Norton said it needed more time to weigh
alternatives to BTR's hostile $1.64 billion takeover bid.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 139,340,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2707.21, off 20.49; transportation 1183.14, up 0.89;
utilities 214.66, up 0.31.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3308.57, off
10.05.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.44, up 0.70; spot
index 131.90, up 0.11.
   Dollar: 158.35 yen, up 2.00; 1.6940 marks, unchanged.
</TEXT>
