900402-0007.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Hallmark Sweetens
   Offer for Junk Bonds
   Issued by Univision
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<IN>
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Hallmark Cards Inc. sweetened its bid
to buy back at a discount $270 million of junk bonds issued
by its majority-owned Univision Holdings subsidiary.
   The closely held greeting-card concern also turned up the
heat on reluctant bondholders, who tendered only a small
fraction of the bonds under the earlier proposal despite
repeated extensions, by announcing that Univision will file
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy-law protection from creditors if
the modified bid isn't accepted.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Hallmark launched the tender offer in February, as part of
an attempt to rescue its investment in Univision. Hallmark
holds a 63.5% stake in the financially troubled operator of a
Spanish-language broadcast network.
   Hallmark's new bid calls for it to pay holders of
Univision's $165 million in senior subordinated discount
notes, due 1998, 55.3 cents on each dollar of face amount --
an increase from the earlier 45 cents. Holders of Univision's
$105 million in subordinated debentures, due 1999, are being
offered 31.5 cents on each dollar of face amount, up from the
previous 30 cents. The offers are scheduled to expire at
12:01 a.m. April 13; holders of the senior notes are being
offered accrued interest from Feb. 1, but the offer for the
subordinated notes doesn't include any such accrual.
   In New York, Wilbur Ross, senior managing director of
Rothschild Inc., who represents holders of a majority of
Univision's two debt issues, said the group views the latest
proposal "as a constructive change, made in good faith."
   He added, however, that the bondholders still have
questions about the allocation of the funds between the two
issues, and the total amount to be offered for the debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900402-0006
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900402-0006.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Car Sales in Europe
   Rose 2.1% in February
   From a Year Earlier
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7H
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Sales of new cars in Europe rose 2.1% in
February from a year earlier, with most motor industry
experts now bullish about continued growth in West Germany
and France throughout 1990, which could lend balance to
downturns expected elsewhere in Europe.
   Despite a seasonal slackening in sales that pushed the
February totals 8.2% below January's, most analysts regarded
the performance as healthy.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "I'm reasonably pleased with these figures," said Rob
Golding, motors analyst with Warburg Securities Ltd. in
London, echoing the sentiment of other sector watchers.
   Industry and government statistics from 12 countries that
normally account for 94% of non-Communist Europe's passenger
car sales showed new-car registrations totaled 1,040,000 in
February, falling from 1,130,000 in January and up from
1,020,000 a year earlier.
   In February, sales were off on the year in four of the
countries included in the survey: Portugal, Spain, Sweden and
the U.K. West Germany posted a modest 3.7% advance, while
France rose 10% and Italy climbed 11%.
   Britain and France contributed largely to the decline from
January, with interest rate-pressure on consumers trimming
sales in the U.K. by 19%. The residual effects of a civil
service strike in December obscured analysis of French sales
figures, which were down by 18% from January, experts said.
   Analysts' forecasts for sales in 1990 range between a 4%
decline and 4% growth. Most reckoned that a slowdown
threatening for the past several months would pull down sales
for the year and leave growth this year below the 3.4% seen
in 1989.
   However, "even two months (into 1990) is probably not
enough to give us a firm view about what is going on," said
Susanne Oliver of Britain's Hoare Govett Ltd.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
